<dl id="n36013c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36013c">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36013c"> 13(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> diwan-i-Am ~ <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n36013c"><li>FW 536.18 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/lexrB.htm#n36013c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rB/l39rB.htm#n36013c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n36013c">MS BL 47484b-363</ms> </li><li>JJA 59:111 <a name="rBd12y" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rBd12y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rB/rBd12.htm#n36013c">Draft: III&sect;3B.12</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">The imperial palace (1638-1648), now known as the &ldquo;Fort&rdquo;, is situated on the east of the city, and abuts directly on the river. It consists at present of bare and ugly British barracks, maong which are scattered exquisite gems of oriental architecture. The two most famous among its buildings are the <mark>Diwan-i-Am or Hall of Public Audience</mark>, and the Diwan-i-Khas or Hall of Private Audience. &hellip; It is in this hall that the famous inscription &ldquo;If a paradise be on the face of the earth, it is this, it is this, it is this,&rdquo; still exists. <small> &ldquo;DELHI&rdquo; <a name="EBDH" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBDH"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 954d-955a</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
